# Handoff checklist (mandatory before commit, push, or merge)

**Branch policy:** Complete this checklist **before** any `git commit`, `git push`, or merge to **`main`** on a feature slice — not only when the user asks for a handoff. Handoff first; git second.

When you are writing or updating a handoff note (e.g. **`doc/handoff/*-HANDOFF-*.md`** / **`doc/handoff/HANDOFF-*.md`** or **`.cursor/handoff/*-handoff-*.md`** / **`.cursor/handoff/handoff-*.md`** — often **gitignored**, not on **`main`**) or **AGENT_HANDOFF** "Current state":

## When to create a handoff (timing)

- **Right time:** You are at a real stopping point: scope is done **or** you are intentionally handing off **mid-flight** with a clear label (e.g. **WIP**, **blocked**, **needs decision**).
- **Wrong time:** Do **not** write a handoff that reads "ship complete" if delivery is not actually finished (e.g. commits on `main` that were never pushed, CI not run, or known follow-ups omitted). If work is incomplete, **say so explicitly** in **Ship status** or a **Not done** section at the top — not only in **Next up**.
- **Git order:** Handoff note + tracked doc updates (steps 1–6 and bullets below) come **before** commit, push, or merge. Do **not** commit until the handoff note records review, tech debt, and test results.
- **Push:** After handoff is complete and you merged to **`main`**, run **`git push origin main`** before ending unless the user asked you not to push, or push failed (then record the failure and that **`main` is ahead of origin**).

**You must run all four and record results in the handoff note. Do not skip any.**

1. **Code review** — Use the **code-reviewer** skill (`.cursor/skills/code-reviewer/SKILL.md`). Review the changed or relevant code since last handoff (or main branch). Output PASS/WARN/FAIL and a short summary. Put the summary in the handoff note under **Code review**.
2. **Tech debt evaluation** — Use the **tech-debt-evaluator** skill (`.cursor/skills/tech-debt-evaluator/SKILL.md`). Assess current debt; produce prioritized list. Put the short summary or "Do first" items in the handoff note under **Tech debt**.
   - If a “Do first” item persists across handoffs or blocks progress, promote it into `TECH_DEBT.md` (ranked).
3. **Tests / coverage** — Run the **merge-ready** command documented in **AGENT_HANDOFF.md** / **TEST_PLAN.md** (e.g. `npm run ci` if that is your gate). Note whether Tier 1 is green and, if useful, a one-line summary. Put in the handoff note under **Code coverage** (or **Tests**).
4. **Project readiness (optional)** — If you maintain a readiness checklist or skill for this product, use it and put the summary under **Project readiness**. Otherwise note "N/A" or skip that section.
5. **Security review (when relevant)** — If the work touched credentials, logging, remote access, networking, firewall, or installed software, run a lightweight **security-reviewer** pass and record PASS/WARN/FAIL.

6. **Tier 2 (integration / E2E) if needed** — If you added or changed behavior that requires integration or E2E validation, run the Tier 2 command from TEST_PLAN.md. Note in the handoff whether Tier 2 was run and the result. See `.cursor/rules/testing.mdc` and TEST_PLAN.md.

7. **Write handoff note** — Create or update **`doc/handoff/`** or `.cursor/handoff/NNNN-handoff-YYYY-MM-DD_HHmm.md` with review, tech debt, tests, ship status, and next steps.

Then update tracked docs (still **before** git):

- Update **PM_PLAN** when scope changed
- Update **[doc/PROJECT_STATUS.md](../../doc/PROJECT_STATUS.md)** and **AGENT_HANDOFF.md** → *Current state* (required — contributor-visible truth on GitHub)

**Only after the handoff note and tracked docs are complete:**

8. **Git commit** — Stage and `git commit` with a short message (merge-ready gate must still be green).
9. **Push + merge** — Push feature branch; merge to **`main`**; **`git push origin main`**. See **AGENT_HANDOFF.md** → *Git workflow*. Treat "committed but not pushed" as **unfinished** unless the user asked to stop before push.

When you summarize **Done this session** for humans, use the **two-audience** approach (see **techwriter** skill → *Dual-audience blurbs*).

**Filename and timestamp:** Prefer **`doc/handoff/NNNN-HANDOFF-YYYY-MM-DD_HHmm.md`** (monotonic `NNNN`, date, 24h time — Windows-safe) so multiple handoffs per day get unique files. Add a **`Recorded:`** line under the H1 (ISO-8601 or local offset). See **AGENT_HANDOFF.md** → handoff protocol.
